{
  "answer": "To accurately understand foundational theology, the Quran directs believers to consult knowledgeable individuals and emphasizes the critical need for clear, accessible communication. \n\n**Relying on People of Knowledge**\n* **Seeking Expertise:** Both Surah An-Nahl 16:43 and Surah Al-Anbiya 21:7 explicitly command believers to \"ask the people of the message if you do not know\" [1, 2]. \n* **Resolving Doubt:** If doubts about the revelation arise, Surah Yunus 10:94 advises consulting \"those who have been reading the Scripture before you\" to find clarity [3]. \n* **Firmness in Faith:** Surah Al Imran 3:7 praises \"those firm in knowledge\" for properly understanding and believing in all of God's verses, contrasting them with those who exploit unclear verses to create discord [4].\n\n**The Need for Clear Language**\n* **Speaking the Audience's Language:** Surah Ibrahim 14:4 establishes that God \"did not send any messenger except [speaking] in the language of his people to state clearly for them\" [5]. This anchors the necessity of translating and conveying theology in a way the audience naturally comprehends.\n* **Clarity for Understanding:** The Quran repeatedly stresses that it was revealed in a \"clear Arabic language\" specifically so that its original audience might understand it [6-8]. \n* **Avoiding Confusion:** Surah Fussilat 41:44 notes that if the Quran had been revealed in a foreign language, the people would have justifiably objected, asking, \"Why are its verses not explained in detail [in our language]?\" [9]. \n* **The Duty to Explain:** The role of the Prophet was not just to deliver the text, but to explain it. Surah An-Nahl 16:44 states he was sent to \"make clear to the people what was sent down to them\" so that they might give it proper thought [10].",
  "conversation_id": "b75c54d4-0ca8-4686-8f68-eef116d359e6",
